approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. NOTE: If `amount` is the maximum `uint256`, the allowance is not updated on `transferFrom`. This is semantically equivalent to an infinite approval. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

balanceOf(address,bool).details: Returns the amount of tokens owned by `account`. If includeUnsettled is false, then it returns the settled balance.

baseToken().details: returns the address of the base token this contract wraps.

cancelOwnershipHandover().details: Cancels the two-step ownership handover to the caller, if any.

closeCase(bool,address,(address,uint256,.details: called when a case is closed after a freeze.

params.freezes: - contains the info of all accounts and amounts that need to be frozen (and potentially recovered).  All items must already be frozen in order to be unfrozen.
params.recover: - if true, then returns the funds back to the victim.
params.victim: - address of the victim who will receive the stolen funds.

completeOwnershipHandover(address).details: Allows the owner to complete the two-step ownership handover to `pendingOwner`. Reverts if there is no existing ownership handover requested by `pendingOwner`.

constructor.details: Required by `RecoverableWrapper` and `AxelarGMPExecutable` deps to write immutable vars to bytecode

decimals().details: Returns the decimals places of the token.

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

execute(bytes32,string,string,bytes).details: This function ensures the call is approved by Axelar Gateway before execution. It uses a hash of the payload for validation and internally calls _execute for the actual command execution. Reverts if the validation fails.

params.commandId: The identifier of the command to execute.
params.payload: The payload of the command to be executed.
params.sourceAddress: The address on the source chain that sent the command.
params.sourceChain: The name of the source chain from which the command originated.

freeze((address,uint256,uint128)[]).details: Example of a freeze function, but this can be implemented in other however way the dev would like.

params.freezes: - contains the info of all the accounts and amounts that need to be frozen.

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

initialize(string,string,address,uint16,.details: This function and all functions invoked within are only available on devnet and testnet Since it will never change, no assembly workaround function such as `setMaxToClean()` is implemented

owner().details: Returns the owner of the contract.

ownershipHandoverExpiresAt(address).details: Returns the expiry timestamp for the two-step ownership handover to `pendingOwner`.

proxiableUUID().details: Implementation of the ERC1822 {proxiableUUID} function. This returns the storage slot used by the implementation. It is used to validate the implementation's compatibility when performing an upgrade. IMPORTANT: A proxy pointing at a proxiable contract should not be considered proxiable itself, because this risks bricking a proxy that upgrades to it, by delegating to itself until out of gas. Thus it is critical that this function revert if invoked through a proxy. This is guaranteed by the `notDelegated` modifier.

renounceOwnership().details: Allows the owner to renounce their ownership.

requestOwnershipHandover().details: Request a two-step ownership handover to the caller. The request will automatically expire in 48 hours (172800 seconds) by default.

params.includeUnsettled: - if false, then return just spendable settled funds.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `to` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transfer(address,uint256,bool).details: Moves `amount` tokens from the caller's account to `to`. if `includeUnsettled` is false, it will only transfer out of settled funds. Returns a boolean value indicating whether the operation succeeded. Emits a {TransferSettled} event, or both {TransferSettled} and {TransferUnsettled} events.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}. NOTE: Does not update the allowance if the current allowance is the maximum `uint256`. Requirements: - `from` and `to` cannot be the zero address. - `from` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``from``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256,boo.details: Moves `amount` tokens from `from` to `to` using the allowance mechanism. `amount` is then deducted from the caller's allowance. if `includeUnsettled` is false, the allowance must also be settled-only. Returns a boolean value indicating whether the operation succeeded. Emits a {Transfer} event.

transferOwnership(address).details: Allows the owner to transfer the ownership to `newOwner`.

params.to: - the address to send unwrapped tokens to

upgradeToAndCall(address,bytes).details: Upgrade the implementation of the proxy to `newImplementation`, and subsequently execute the function call encoded in `data`. Calls {_authorizeUpgrade}. Emits an {Upgraded} event.

balanceOf(address).notice: Defaults to not using unsettled funds

constructor.notice: For use when deployed as singleton

disableUnwrap().notice: Disables all future unwrap calls for the caller's account.  This is an optional extra safety precaution for certain addresses (i.e. contracts) that  should only issue out ERC20R tokens in wrapped form, preventing bad actors from  calling unwrap on its behalf in the future.

distributeStakeReward(address,uint256).notice: May only be called by the ConsensusRegistry as part of its `claimStakeRewards()` flow

execute(bytes32,string,string,bytes).notice: Executes the cross-chain command after validating it with the Axelar Gateway.

gateway().notice: Returns the address of the AxelarGMPGateway contract.

governanceAddress().notice: Address of the governance that is allowed to call freeze and closeCase

initialize(string,string,address,uint16,.notice: Replaces `constructor` for use when deployed as a proxy implementation`RW::constructor()` accepts a `baseERC20_` parameter which is set as an immutable variable in bytecode

name().notice: Overrides `RecoverableWrapper::ERC20::name()` which accesses a private var

nonce(address).notice: Each time an account receives ERC20R tokens, this nonce increments. This may be useful in contexts where another party wants to evaluate the clawback risk of an account's  tokens, based on the account's current state.

recoverableWindow().notice: Length of recoverable window after each transaction, in seconds

setMaxToClean(uint16).notice: Workaround function to alter `RecoverableWrapper::MAX_TO_CLEAN` without forking audited code Provided because `MAX_TO_CLEAN` may require alteration in the future, as opposed to `baseERC20`,

spendableBalanceOf(address,bool).notice: Returns the current spendable balance of the account, not including any frozen funds.

symbol().notice: Overrides `RecoverableWrapper::ERC20::name()` which accesses a private var

transfer(address,uint256).notice: Defaults to not using unsettled funds

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).notice: Defaults to only using settled funds.

unwrap(uint256).notice: Allows caller to unwrap their own recoverable tokens back to the base token

unwrapTo(address,uint256).notice: First unwraps caller's recoverable tokens and then sends base token to another address

wrap(uint256).notice: Allows caller to wrap their own base tokens
